nd of human communication, Discourse Markers are part of the game. This omnipresence informs us of a crucial inherent aspect of human language. Yet, as a linguistic category, Discourse Markers remain underdetermined. To gain deeper insight into this complex linguistic category, more systematic work is needed on the production and on the interpretation of Discourse Markers in a variety of situational settings, resorting to different methodological approaches. The contributions in this volume aim at drawing more attention to the double face of Discourse Markers, namely as signals intentionally used by the speaker to facilitate the addressee’s interpretation of the discourse, but also as potential traces of the speaker’s production difficulties. The combination of experimental and corpus-based approaches and the focus on processing of Discourse Markers in both production and comprehension makes this volume a unique contribution in answering the question why we use Discourse Markers in certain situations, but also when we do not.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 4aDiskursmarker. 4aKorpusanalyse. 4aSprachverarbeitung. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aComputational Applications.  aCorpus Analysis.  aDiscourse Markers.  aDiscourse Processing.1 aAllein, Liesbeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAriel, Mira, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlochowiak, Joanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBroisson, Zoé, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCruz, Adriana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuenca, Maria-Josep, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuenca, Mar